5000|$|... 16 mm {{film is a}} {{historically}} popular and economical gauge of film. 16 mm refers to {{the width of the}} film; other common film gauges include 8 and 35 mm. It is generally used for non-theatrical (e.g., industrial, educational) film-making, or for low-budget motion pictures. It also existed as a popular amateur or home movie-making format for several decades, alongside 8 mm film and later Super 8 film. Eastman Kodak released the first 16 mm [...] "outfit" [...] in 1923, consisting of a camera, projector, <b>tripod,</b> <b>screen</b> and splicer, for $335. RCA-Victor introduced a 16 mm sound movie projector in 1932, and developed an optical sound-on-film 16 mm camera, released in 1935.|$|E

